metadata.name: Traces #186
metadata.description:
Traces is an exploration around movement.
Inspired but motion blur in photography, using lines travelling through obstacles, it can create scenes, sometimes representation of virtual landscapes.

metadata.name: CA Class 4 #94
metadata.description:
Class 4 cellular automatons produce a combination of randomness and order.  All of the class 4 rules’ patterns are more complex than their Class 3 cousins.  Class 4 structures emerge, move around, and interact with one another before petering out or evolving.  Whereas class 3 automatons are analogous to irrational numbers, class 4 automata behave more like living organisms.

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

Props and attribution to Stephen Wolfram, Johnny Von Neumann and Nils Aall Barricelli

objkt.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #75

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #75
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

metadata.name: CPU Die Shots #14
metadata.description:
Two color palettes (2 Bits and Acetone) and a unique CPU die shot is generated based on unique hash seeds.

The definition of a die (wikipedia):
A die, in the context of integrated circuits, is a small block of semiconducting material on which a given functional circuit is fabricated. Typically, integrated circuits are produced in large batches on a single wafer of electronic-grade silicon (EGS) or other semiconductor (such as GaAs) through processes such as photolithography. The wafer is cut (diced) into many pieces, each containing one copy of the circuit. Each of these pieces is called a die.

Specials
- press "c" to recreate a new Landscape
- press "g" to activate the "Gallery Mode", piece change each 60s

Generative Art created by Michael Vogt (@neophob).

metadata.name: SkeleSteamPunx #114
metadata.description:
Genesis generative image project by @LimnDigital.

65 total unique traits = 2,459,688 possible variations (including backgrounds and base)
52 skull/facial traits = 111,804 possible variations. 
Each trait created via custom VQGAN+CLIP Python code by LimnDigital.
Each trait isolated and manually extracted in Procreate, then randomly assembled via p5.js and custom JavaScript by LimnDigital.

Not associated with Larva Labs, CryptoPunks, or any ‘Skulls’ or ‘Punks’ projects. 

Save your minted Artwork (or any edition) in Live Mode by pressing:
‘s’ or ‘S’ to save at current canvas size.
‘f’ or ‘F’ to save at Full size, 2048 x 2048px.
‘t’ or ‘T’ to save at Twitter Tweet size, 1200 x 1200px.

Saved Artwork filename contains: Project Name, Artist Name, Pixel size, and Unique Hash.

metadata.name: Minimal Surfaces #52
metadata.description:
Minimal surfaces, a gyroid in this case, are mathematical surfaces that minimize their area given a fixed perimeter. Because nature is all about 'being as efficient as possible' minimal surfaces aren't just theoretical, they show up in real life as well. Soap bubbles are an example of a minimal surface. In this set I explore the different looks you can get from the amazing Gyroid surface by looking at cross sections of the structure. 

NOTE: this is completely procedural and while I do my best to shape the possibility space such that you get interesting and beautiful variety, it can happen that something 'broken' shows up. If you get a completely solid colored screen then shoot me a DM on twitter and I'll happily send you something else.
